President Donald Trump hosted Prime Minister Lee Hsien Loong of Singapore at the White House, affirming the strong partnership between the two countries. They discussed various areas of cooperation, including economic, defense, security, and people-to-people relations. They highlighted the success of the United States-Singapore Free Trade Agreement, which has led to a significant increase in bilateral trade. The leaders also emphasized the importance of the defense ties between the two countries, with Singapore hosting the rotational deployment of US military aircraft and ships. They expressed concern about North Korea's nuclear and ballistic missile programs and reaffirmed their commitment to implementing UN Security Council resolutions. The leaders pledged to strengthen cooperation in countering ISIS and addressing cybersecurity threats. They also discussed expanding economic ties and cooperation on tax issues. Both leaders expressed support for the peaceful resolution of disputes in the South China Sea and the need to address the humanitarian situation in Rakhine State. They reaffirmed their commitment to ASEAN centrality and the US-ASEAN strategic partnership. President Trump accepted Prime Minister Lee's invitation to visit Singapore in 2018.